<html><head><meta name="color-scheme" content="light dark"><meta charset="utf-8"></head><body><pre>{"id":1770,"date":"2025-03-08T10:49:35","date_gmt":"2025-03-07T23:49:35","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/?p=1770"},"modified":"2025-03-08T10:49:35","modified_gmt":"2025-03-07T23:49:35","slug":"iwwd2025","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/iwwd2025\/","title":{"rendered":"International Working Women&amp;#8217;s Day 2025: Despite It All, We Can Fight Back"},"content":{"rendered":"\n&lt;p&gt;Despite the brunches and pink frosted cupcakes, women in Australia are under threat. Gender based violence is on the rise, abortion rights are still under threat in Australia and mature women are one of the fastest growing homeless demographics. At home women&amp;#8217;s care work is taken for granted, their hidden labour is vital for the running of the economy. At work women are subjected to sexist harassment and discrimination. Whole professions (such as nurses and teachers) associated with women, known as feminised industries, are underpaid due to sexist devalueing of care work.&amp;nbsp; It is laughable to suggest we are in a free and equal society.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;International Working Women&amp;#8217;s Day gives us a chance to reflect on the battles of the past, reflect on women&amp;#8217;s place in society today, and renew our fight for a better future.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;Despite the massive issues facing women, there is resistance. Last year there were mass rallies calling attention to the rise in gender based violence. There were mobilisations against the newly elected LNP government in Queensland to defend abortion. Industrial action by nurses in Victoria was able to secure much needed wage raises for a drastically underpaid feminised industry, moving the dial in bridging the wage gap. Female construction unionist rallied in Queensland demanding legislation on women&amp;#8217;s bathrooms on site, a demand they would go on to win. Despite all that is stacked against women we can fight back.&amp;nbsp;&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;So what&amp;#8217;s the path forward for the struggle? Instead of hoping for female bosses or electing politicians to disappoint us, we need to take action for ourselves. This is difficult to do in isolation, so we need to get organised and band together with people in the same situations as us. The most powerful way to do this is class organisations like trade unions. By fighting alongside our fellow workers, regardless of gender, we increase our power. By struggling together we improve our lives and build solidarity. Building a power of our own we can have real weight to bring to the fights against gender based violence and to secure abortion rights.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n\n&lt;p&gt;Ultimately, the degree to which women&amp;#8217;s autonomy can be expanded is limited by the nature of capitalism. The system depends on the exploitation of women. If we want true freedom, we need to replace it with something better. A system where everyone takes an active role in decision-making, rather than leaving it to politicians: anarchism. A system where workers can manage their work collectively for the good of society, not for profit: communism.&lt;\/p&gt;\n\n\n&lt;div class=\"wp-block-image\"&gt;\n&lt;figure class=\"aligncenter size-full is-resized\"&gt;&lt;img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"879\" height=\"291\" src=\"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/03\/ACM.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-1773\" style=\"width:211px;height:auto\" srcset=\"https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/03\/ACM.png 879w, https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/03\/ACM-300x99.png 300w, https:\/\/melbacg.au\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/03\/ACM-768x254.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 879px) 100vw, 879px\" \/&gt;&lt;\/figure&gt;\n&lt;\/div&gt;\n\n&lt;div class=\"wp-block-image\"&gt;\n&lt;figure class=\"aligncenter size-full is-resized\"&gt;&lt;img loadin